lowerextremityright.textareatext: Darkening of melanocytes or hemosiderin deposits.
Loss of skin color, but no white.
Necrosis due to disrupted blood supply.
Red skin discoloration that blanches with pressure (Diopter positive).
Entire or nearly entire whole body redness.
Bleeding or bruising into the skin that does not blanch with pressure (Diopter negative).
The form or appearance of a skin lesion.
An area with color change less than or equal to 2 cm diameter.
A large area of color with a smooth surface.
Small palpable lesion less than 1.5 cm in diameter; raised or multiple.
Enlargement of a papule in three dimensions; solid.
Papule or nodule with fluid; fluctuant.
Flat lesion greater than 0.5 cm diameter, usually elevated; well or ill defined border.
Variegated with mixed color and pigmentation.
Small fluid filled blisters less than 0.5 cm diameter; single or multiple.
Large fluid filled blister; single compartment or multiloculated.
Palpably thickened skin with increased skin markings and scale.
Rough surface with yellow or brown color.
Crack within the dermis or epithelium.
Full thickness loss of the epidermis or epithelium.
Thermally induced damage to the skin.
First degree; red without blisters. Blanches.
Second degree; red with clear blisters. Blanches.
Second degree. Yellow or white. Some blanching. May blister.
Third degree. Stiff; white or brown. No blanching.
Extends into fat, muscle and bone. Dry.
How the lesions are scattered or spread out.
Distal portions of limbs (hands, feet) and head (ears, nose)
Embryonic skin migration pattern that disease may follow.
Flexor surfaces of limbs including body folds i.e. groin.
On or in a wound location.

options: Lower leg extensor and flexor surfaces

lowerextremityright.textareatext: Body locations injured from the prone rest position.
Similar right and left pattern or involvement. For example, if the right arm and the left arm both display lesions in the same area, then the lesion distribution is considered symmetrical.
Pattern limited to one side of the affected area.
